{{Shrine |Name= Saruta Shrine |image= [[Image:Saruda-jinjya-shrine,choshi-city,japan.JPG|250px]] |Location= {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|de|Chiba-Präfektur|ja|千葉県|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Choshi City|de|Choshi Stadt|ja|銚子市|12=draft|12=draft}} Saruta-machi 1677 |Coordinates= {{WikiCoordinatesTwoTierDMS|35|44|50|N|140|44|0|E|scale:25000}} |Enshrined Deities= {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|de|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|サルタヒコ|lt=Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt_ja=猿田彦大神|lt_de=Sarutahiko Ōkami|12=draft|12=draft}}・{{ill|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|de|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|ja|アメノウズメ|lt=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=天鈿女命|lt_de=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}・{{ill|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|de|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=菊理媛命|lt_de=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}} |Shrine Rank= UnRanked Shrine |Established= 25th year of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Kaiser Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} |Main Hall= Nagare-zukuri |Alternate Name= |Annual Festival= November 15 |Sacred Rites= Shikinen Taisai Kamiyuki-sai }}
'''Saruta Shrine''' (猿田神社) is a {{ill|Shrine|de|Schrein|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in Saruta-machi, {{ill|Choshi City|de|Choshi Stadt|ja|銚子市|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|de|Chiba-Präfektur|ja|千葉県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It has long been venerated for practices such as {{ill|Directional Deity|de|Richtgott|ja|方位神|1=Directional deity|lt=Eight-Directional Protection|lt_ja=八方除け|lt_de=Achtseitiger Schutz|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its principal deities are {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|de|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|サルタヒコ|lt=Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt_ja=猿田彦大神|lt_de=Sarutahiko Ōkami|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|de|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|ja|アメノウズメ|lt=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=天鈿女命|lt_de=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|de|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=菊理媛命|lt_de=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == According to shrine tradition, it was founded on November 25 in the 25th year of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Kaiser Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, and during the reign of {{ill|Empress Jingū|de|Kaiserin Jingū|ja|神功皇后|12=draft|12=draft}}, it became a branch shrine of {{ill|Ikuta Shrine|de|Ikuta-Schrein|ja|生田神社|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the 2nd year of {{ill|Daido|de|Daido|ja|大同 (日本)|lt=Daido|lt_ja=大同|lt_de=Daido|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|807 AD|de|807 n. Chr.|ja|807年|12=draft|12=draft}}), a shrine building was constructed, and during the {{ill|Kōhei Era|de|Kōhei-Periode|ja|康平|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|1058 AD|de|1058 n. Chr.|ja|1058年|12=draft|12=draft}} – {{ill|1065 AD|de|1065 n. Chr.|ja|1065年|12=draft|12=draft}}), {{ill|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|de|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|ja|源頼義|12=draft|12=draft}} donated {{ill|Kanda|de|Kanda|ja|神田|12=draft|12=draft}}. Since the {{ill|Kamakura period|de|Kamakura-Zeit|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the warrior families ({{ill|Buke (Japan)|de|Kriegerfamilien|ja|武家|12=draft|lt=Buke|12=draft}}) have shown strong devotion, and it is said that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|de|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft|12=draft}} also made donations, with {{ill|Ashikaga Harushi|de|Ashikaga Harushi|ja|足利晴氏|12=draft|12=draft}} having offered a golden seal that still exists today.
In the 9th year of the {{ill|Eiroku Era|de|Eiroku-Periode|ja|永禄|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|1566 AD|de|1566 n. Chr.|ja|1566年|12=draft|12=draft}}), the shrine building was burned down in a battle between the {{ill|Kaijō Clan|de|Kaijō-Clan|ja|海上氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Awa Masaki Clan|de|Awa Masaki-Clan|ja|安房正木氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. Although it was rebuilt during the {{ill|Genki Era|de|Genki-Periode|ja|元亀|12=draft|12=draft}}, it was again burned down in the 1st year of the {{ill|Tenshō Era|de|Tenshō-Periode|ja|天正|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|1573 AD|de|1573 n. Chr.|ja|1573年|12=draft|12=draft}}) and rebuilt in the following 2nd year of Tenshō ({{ill|1574 AD|de|1574 n. Chr.|ja|1574年|12=draft|12=draft}}). The current main hall was reconstructed in the 8th year of the {{ill|Enpō Era|de|Enpō-Periode|ja|延宝|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|1680 AD|de|1680 n. Chr.|ja|1680年|12=draft|12=draft}}). Additionally, in the 19th year of Tenshō ({{ill|1591 AD|de|1591 n. Chr.|ja|1591年|12=draft|12=draft}}), {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|de|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft|12=draft}} donated 30 stones of {{ill|Red Seal Land|de|Rotsiegel-Land|ja|朱印地|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Every 60 years, in the {{ill|Kōshin Year|de|Kōshin-Jahr|ja|庚申|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Shikinen Taisai Kamiyuki-sai is held.
== Cultural Properties == * One plaque from the annex of the Saruta Shrine main hall ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#建造物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|lt_ja=千葉県指定有形文化財|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|12=draft|12=draft}}) * The forest of Saruta Shrine ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#天然記念物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|lt_ja=千葉県指定天然記念物|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|12=draft|12=draft}})
== Access == * 5-minute walk from {{ill|Saruta Station|de|Saruta Bahnhof|ja|猿田駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Sōbu Main Line|de|Sōbu-Hauptlinie|ja|総武本線|12=draft|12=draft}}. * From either {{ill|National Route 126|de|Nationalstraße 126|ja|国道126号|12=draft|12=draft}} at Asahi City's Ato or {{ill|National Route 356|de|Nationalstraße 356|ja|国道356号|12=draft|12=draft}} at Choshi City's Nojiri, via the {{ill|Choshi-Asahi Line (Chiba Prefectural Road 71)|de|Choshi-Asahi-Linie (Chiba-Prefekturstraße 71)|ja|千葉県道71号銚子旭線|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Other == * There is a bridge called Sakushinbashi on the approach road that spans the JR {{ill|Sōbu Main Line|de|Sōbu-Hauptlinie|ja|総武本線|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was constructed by the railway company when the {{ill|Sōbu Railway (first generation)|de|Sōbu-Eisenbahn (Erste Generation)|ja|総武鉄道 (初代)|lt=Sōbu Railway|lt_ja=総武鉄道|lt_de=Sōbu Eisenbahn|12=draft|12=draft}} was extended to {{ill|Choshi Station|de|Choshi Bahnhof|ja|銚子駅|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|1897 AD|de|1897 n. Chr.|ja|1897年|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji Era|de|Meiji-Periode|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 30), which resulted in the approach road being divided. * Due to the remnants of {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|de|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine office is closed on Butsumetsu ({{ill|Butsumetsu (Buddhist calendar)|de|Butsumetsu|ja|六曜#仏滅|lt=Butsumetsu|lt_ja=仏滅|lt_de=Butsumetsu|12=draft|12=draft}}) day.
== References == {{No footnotes|date=2020年2月|section=1}} * 『National Shrine Directory, Volume 1』, National Shrine Directory Publishing Society History Center, Showa 52. * 『Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names, Volume 12: Chiba Prefecture』, Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names Editorial Committee, Showa 59.
