{{Shrine |Name= Saruta Shrine |image= [[Image:Saruda-jinjya-shrine,choshi-city,japan.JPG|250px]] |Location= {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|de|Chiba-Präfektur|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture|qq=}} {{ill|Choshi City|de|Choshi Stadt|ja|銚子市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choshi City|qq=}} Saruta-machi 1677 |Coordinates= {{WikiCoordinatesTwoTierDMS|35|44|50|N|140|44|0|E|scale:25000}} |Enshrined Deities= {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|de|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|サルタヒコ|lt=Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt_ja=猿田彦大神|lt_de=Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=}}・{{ill|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|de|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|ja|アメノウズメ|lt=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=天鈿女命|lt_de=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|qq=}}・{{ill|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|de|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=菊理媛命|lt_de=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|qq=}} |Shrine Rank= Unranked Shrine |Established= 25th year of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Kaiser Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Suinin|qq=}} |Main Hall= Nagare-zukuri |Alternate Name= |Annual Festival= November 15 |Sacred Rites= Shikinen Taisai Kamiyuki-sai }}
'''Saruta Shrine''' (猿田神社) is a {{ill|Shrine|de|Schrein|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shrine|qq=}} located in Saruta-machi, {{ill|Choshi City|de|Choshi Stadt|ja|銚子市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choshi City|qq=}} of {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|de|Chiba-Präfektur|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture|qq=}}. It has long been venerated for practices such as {{ill|Directional Deity|de|Richtgott|ja|方位神|1=Directional deity|lt=Eight-Directional Protection|lt_ja=八方除け|lt_de=Achtseitiger Schutz|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Directional Deity|13=User:Immanuelle/Directional deity|qq=}}. Its principal deities are {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|de|Sarutahiko Ōkami|ja|サルタヒコ|lt=Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt_ja=猿田彦大神|lt_de=Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=}}, {{ill|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|de|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|ja|アメノウズメ|lt=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=天鈿女命|lt_de=Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|de|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|ja|菊理媛神|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|lt_ja=菊理媛命|lt_de=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.
== History == According to shrine tradition, it was founded on November 25 in the 25th year of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|de|Kaiser Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Suinin|qq=}}, and during the reign of {{ill|Empress Jingū|de|Kaiserin Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Jingū|qq=}}, it became a branch shrine of {{ill|Ikuta Shrine|de|Ikuta-Schrein|ja|生田神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikuta Shrine|qq=}}. In the 2nd year of {{ill|Daido|de|Daido|ja|大同 (日本)|lt=Daido|lt_ja=大同|lt_de=Daido|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daido|qq=}} ({{ill|807 AD|de|807 n. Chr.|ja|807年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/807 AD|qq=}}), a shrine building was constructed, and during the {{ill|Kōhei Era|de|Kōhei-Periode|ja|康平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōhei Era|qq=}} ({{ill|1058 AD|de|1058 n. Chr.|ja|1058年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1058 AD|qq=}} – {{ill|1065 AD|de|1065 n. Chr.|ja|1065年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1065 AD|qq=}}), {{ill|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|de|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|ja|源頼義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|qq=}} donated {{ill|Kanda|de|Kanda|ja|神田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanda|qq=}}. Since the {{ill|Kamakura period|de|Kamakura-Zeit|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, the warrior families ({{ill|Buke (Japan)|de|Kriegerfamilien|ja|武家|qq=draft|lt=Buke|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buke (Japan)|qq=}}) have shown strong devotion, and it is said that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|de|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} also made donations, with {{ill|Ashikaga Harushi|de|Ashikaga Harushi|ja|足利晴氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga Harushi|qq=}} having offered a golden seal that still exists today.
In the 9th year of the {{ill|Eiroku Era|de|Eiroku-Periode|ja|永禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiroku Era|qq=}} ({{ill|1566 AD|de|1566 n. Chr.|ja|1566年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1566 AD|qq=}}), the shrine building was burned down in a battle between the {{ill|Kaijō Clan|de|Kaijō-Clan|ja|海上氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaijō Clan|qq=}} and the {{ill|Awa Masaki Clan|de|Awa Masaki-Clan|ja|安房正木氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awa Masaki Clan|qq=}}. Although it was rebuilt during the {{ill|Genki Era|de|Genki-Periode|ja|元亀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genki Era|qq=}}, it was again burned down in the 1st year of the {{ill|Tenshō Era|de|Tenshō-Periode|ja|天正|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō Era|qq=}} ({{ill|1573 AD|de|1573 n. Chr.|ja|1573年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1573 AD|qq=}}) and rebuilt in the following 2nd year of Tenshō ({{ill|1574 AD|de|1574 n. Chr.|ja|1574年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1574 AD|qq=}}). The current main hall was reconstructed in the 8th year of the {{ill|Enpō Era|de|Enpō-Periode|ja|延宝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enpō Era|qq=}} ({{ill|1680 AD|de|1680 n. Chr.|ja|1680年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1680 AD|qq=}}). Additionally, in the 19th year of Tenshō ({{ill|1591 AD|de|1591 n. Chr.|ja|1591年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1591 AD|qq=}}), {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|de|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Ieyasu|qq=}} donated 30 stones of {{ill|Red Seal Land|de|Rotsiegel-Land|ja|朱印地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Red Seal Land|qq=}}.
Every 60 years, in the {{ill|Kōshin Year|de|Kōshin-Jahr|ja|庚申|1=Kōshin|lt=Yang Metal Monkey|2=ja|3=庚申|4=zh|5=庚申|6=ko|7=경신|lt_ko=경신|8=fr|9=Singe de métal|10=de|11=Metall-Affe|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōshin Year|qq=}}, the Shikinen Taisai Kamiyuki-sai is held.
== Cultural Properties == * One plaque from the annex of the Saruta Shrine main hall ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#建造物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|lt_ja=千葉県指定有形文化財|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|qq=}}) * The forest of Saruta Shrine ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#天然記念物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|lt_ja=千葉県指定天然記念物|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|qq=}})
== Access == * 5-minute walk from {{ill|Saruta Station|de|Saruta Bahnhof|ja|猿田駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saruta Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Sōbu Main Line|de|Sōbu-Hauptlinie|ja|総武本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōbu Main Line|qq=}}. * From either {{ill|National Route 126|de|Nationalstraße 126|ja|国道126号|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 126|qq=}} at Asahi City's Ato or {{ill|National Route 356|de|Nationalstraße 356|ja|国道356号|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Route 356|qq=}} at Choshi City's Nojiri, via the {{ill|Choshi-Asahi Line (Chiba Prefectural Road 71)|de|Choshi-Asahi-Linie (Chiba-Prefekturstraße 71)|ja|千葉県道71号銚子旭線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choshi-Asahi Line (Chiba Prefectural Road 71)|qq=}}.
== Other == * There is a bridge called Sakushinbashi on the approach road that spans the JR {{ill|Sōbu Main Line|de|Sōbu-Hauptlinie|ja|総武本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōbu Main Line|qq=}}. It was constructed by the railway company when the {{ill|Sōbu Railway (first generation)|de|Sōbu-Eisenbahn (Erste Generation)|ja|総武鉄道 (初代)|lt=Sōbu Railway|lt_ja=総武鉄道|lt_de=Sōbu Eisenbahn|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōbu Railway (first generation)|qq=}} was extended to {{ill|Choshi Station|de|Choshi Bahnhof|ja|銚子駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choshi Station|qq=}} in {{ill|1897 AD|de|1897 n. Chr.|ja|1897年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1897 AD|qq=}} ({{ill|Meiji Era|de|Meiji-Periode|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji Era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 30), which resulted in the approach road being divided. * Due to the remnants of {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|de|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=}}, the shrine office is closed on Butsumetsu ({{ill|Butsumetsu (Buddhist calendar)|de|Butsumetsu|ja|六曜#仏滅|lt=Butsumetsu|lt_ja=仏滅|lt_de=Butsumetsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Butsumetsu (Buddhist calendar)|qq=}}) day.
== References == {{No footnotes|date=2020年2月|section=1}} * 『National Shrine Directory, Volume 1』, National Shrine Directory Publishing Society History Center, Showa 52. * 『Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names, Volume 12: Chiba Prefecture』, Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names Editorial Committee, Showa 59.
