'''Saruta Shrine''' (猿田神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shrine]] located in Saruta-machi, [[:en:Chōshi|Choshi City]] of [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]]. It has long been venerated for practices such as {{ill|Directional Deity|de|Richtgott|ja|方位神|1=Directional deity|lt=Eight-Directional Protection|lt_ja=八方除け|lt_de=Achtseitiger Schutz|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Directional Deity|13=User:Immanuelle/Directional deity|qq=}}. Its principal deities are [[:en:Sarutahiko Ōkami|Sarutahiko Ōkami]], [[:en:Ame-no-Uzume|Ame-no-Uzume]], and [[:en:Kukurihime|Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto]].
== History == According to shrine tradition, it was founded on November 25 in the 25th year of [[:en:Emperor Suinin|Emperor Suinin]], and during the reign of [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]], it became a branch shrine of [[:en:Ikuta Shrine|Ikuta Shrine]]. In the 2nd year of [[:en:Daidō|Daido]] ([[:en:807|807 AD]]), a shrine building was constructed, and during the [[:en:Kōhei|Kōhei Era]] ([[:en:1058|1058 AD]] – [[:en:1065|1065 AD]]), [[:en:Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi]] donated [[:en:Kanda|Kanda]]. Since the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], the warrior families ({{ill|Buke (Japan)|de|Kriegerfamilien|ja|武家|qq=draft|lt=Buke|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Buke (Japan)|qq=}}) have shown strong devotion, and it is said that [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]] also made donations, with {{ill|Ashikaga Harushi|de|Ashikaga Harushi|ja|足利晴氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga Harushi|qq=}} having offered a golden seal that still exists today.
In the 9th year of the [[:en:Eiroku|Eiroku Era]] ([[:en:1566|1566 AD]]), the shrine building was burned down in a battle between the {{ill|Kaijō Clan|de|Kaijō-Clan|ja|海上氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaijō Clan|qq=}} and the {{ill|Awa Masaki Clan|de|Awa Masaki-Clan|ja|安房正木氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Awa Masaki Clan|qq=}}. Although it was rebuilt during the [[:en:Genki (era)|Genki Era]], it was again burned down in the 1st year of the [[:en:Tenshō (Momoyama period)|Tenshō Era]] ([[:en:1573|1573 AD]]) and rebuilt in the following 2nd year of Tenshō ([[:en:1574|1574 AD]]). The current main hall was reconstructed in the 8th year of the [[:en:Enpō|Enpō Era]] ([[:en:1680|1680 AD]]). Additionally, in the 19th year of Tenshō ([[:en:1591|1591 AD]]), [[:en:Tokugawa Ieyasu|Tokugawa Ieyasu]] donated 30 stones of {{ill|Red Seal Land|de|Rotsiegel-Land|ja|朱印地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Red Seal Land|qq=}}.
Every 60 years, in the {{ill|Kōshin Year|de|Kōshin-Jahr|ja|庚申|1=Kōshin|lt=Yang Metal Monkey|2=ja|3=庚申|4=zh|5=庚申|6=ko|7=경신|lt_ko=경신|8=fr|9=Singe de métal|10=de|11=Metall-Affe|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōshin Year|qq=}}, the Shikinen Taisai Kamiyuki-sai is held.
== Cultural Properties == * One plaque from the annex of the Saruta Shrine main hall ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#建造物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|lt_ja=千葉県指定有形文化財|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designierte greifbare Kulturimmobilie|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture-designated Tangible Cultural Property|qq=}}) * The forest of Saruta Shrine ({{ill|Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|de|Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#天然記念物|lt=Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|lt_ja=千葉県指定天然記念物|lt_de=Chiba-Präfektur-designiertes Naturdenkmal|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chiba Prefecture-designated Natural Monument|qq=}})
== Access == * 5-minute walk from [[:en:Saruda Station|Saruta Station]] on the [[:en:Sōbu Main Line|Sōbu Main Line]]. * From either [[:en:Japan National Route 126|National Route 126]] at Asahi City's Ato or [[:en:Japan National Route 356|National Route 356]] at Choshi City's Nojiri, via the {{ill|Choshi-Asahi Line (Chiba Prefectural Road 71)|de|Choshi-Asahi-Linie (Chiba-Prefekturstraße 71)|ja|千葉県道71号銚子旭線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Choshi-Asahi Line (Chiba Prefectural Road 71)|qq=}}.
== Other == * There is a bridge called Sakushinbashi on the approach road that spans the JR [[:en:Sōbu Main Line|Sōbu Main Line]]. It was constructed by the railway company when the {{ill|Sōbu Railway (first generation)|de|Sōbu-Eisenbahn (Erste Generation)|ja|総武鉄道 (初代)|lt=Sōbu Railway|lt_ja=総武鉄道|lt_de=Sōbu Eisenbahn|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōbu Railway (first generation)|qq=}} was extended to [[:en:Chōshi Station|Choshi Station]] in [[:en:1897|1897 AD]] ([[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 30), which resulted in the approach road being divided. * Due to the remnants of [[:en:Shinbutsu-shūgō|Shinbutsu-shūgō]], the shrine office is closed on Butsumetsu ({{ill|Butsumetsu (Buddhist calendar)|de|Butsumetsu|ja|六曜#仏滅|lt=Butsumetsu|lt_ja=仏滅|lt_de=Butsumetsu|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Butsumetsu (Buddhist calendar)|qq=}}) day.
== References == {{No footnotes|date=2020年2月|section=1}} * 『National Shrine Directory, Volume 1』, National Shrine Directory Publishing Society History Center, Showa 52. * 『Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names, Volume 12: Chiba Prefecture』, Kadokawa Great Dictionary of Japanese Place Names Editorial Committee, Showa 59.
== External Links == * [http://www.choshikanko.com/extra/saruta/ Choshi City Saruta Shrine]
